Building a rich text editor with Tiptap usually means creating the toolbar, menus, themes, image handling, and content renderer yourself.
tiptap-react-ui packages those pieces into a ready-to-use React library.
What’s included?
The library provides two editor styles:

• A traditional rich text editor with a full toolbar

• A Notion-like editor with slash commands and a bubble menu
It also supports tables, image uploads, YouTube embeds, code highlighting, text colors, dark mode, word counts, and HTML or JSON rendering.
Getting started
Install the library and its Tiptap peer dependencies:
npm install tiptap-react-ui @tiptap/core@3 @tiptap/pm@3 @tiptap/react@3Import the included stylesheet:
import "tiptap-react-ui/style.css";Then add the editor:
import {
RichTextEditor,
useTiptapEditor,
} from "tiptap-react-ui";export default function Editor() {
const { editor, isEditorLoading } = useTiptapEditor({
placeholder: "Start writing...",
}); if (isEditorLoading) return null; return (
<RichTextEditor
editor={editor}
theme="violet"
mode="light"
/>
);
}Basic Usage
import "tiptap-react-ui/style.css";
import { RichTextEditor, useTiptapEditor } from "tiptap-react-ui";export default function Editor() {
const { editor, isEditorLoading } = useTiptapEditor({
placeholder: "Write something...",
});
if (isEditorLoading) return null;
return (
<RichTextEditor
editor={editor}
theme="violet"
mode="light"
wrapperClassName="max-w-5xl mx-auto"
/>
);
}
For a Notion-style experience:
import {
NotionEditor,
useTiptapEditor,
} from "tiptap-react-ui";export default function Editor() {
const { editor } = useTiptapEditor({
placeholder: "Write, or type '/' for commands",
}); return <NotionEditor editor={editor} />;
}Basic Usage
import "tiptap-react-ui/style.css";
import { NotionEditor, useTiptapEditor } from "tiptap-react-ui";export default function NotionPage() {
const { editor, isEditorLoading } = useTiptapEditor({
placeholder: "Write, type '/' for commands",
});
if (isEditorLoading) return null;
return <NotionEditor editor={editor} className="max-w-4xl mx-auto" />;
}
The package includes compiled and scoped styles, so projects do not need Tailwind CSS or shadcn/ui to use it.
Rendering saved content
Saved HTML and Tiptap JSON can also be displayed using the included renderers:
import { RenderHTML, RenderJSON } from "tiptap-react-ui";<RenderJSON content={jsonContent} />;
<RenderHTML content={htmlContent} />;Is it worth trying?
If a project needs a capable React editor without building the entire interface around Tiptap, this library is a useful starting point. It remains customizable while taking care of much of the repetitive UI work.
tiptap-react-ui supports React 18 and 19 and is available under the MIT license.

